cs.CY, cs.POL, cs.SI, cs.DL, cs.IR 

This paper is likely to belong to the cs.CY (Computers and Society) category because it examines the use of science in policymaking, which has implications for the intersection of technology and society. It could also belong to cs.POL (Computational Social Science and Social Computing) because it analyzes the effects of political attention on the use of science in policymaking. Additionally, the paper uses computational methods to analyze the citation activity in regulatory impact analyses, which could place it in the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) or cs.DL (Digital Libraries) categories. Finally, the paper could also be relevant to the cs.IR (Information Retrieval) category because it involves analyzing the use of scientific research in policy justifications.
